english:
  title: Reflections on My Heart
  author: Yun Sojong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A lonely man in rough garb kneels before the throne,
    And the royal voice, gentle as jade, bestows the rank of Remonstrator upon me.
    Yet what heart can I harbor for my own life?
    I have sworn myself anew to ancient virtue before heaven and earth.
    Unable to present the great memorial on the realm's fate,
    I have betrayed the Emperor's grace in raising me up.
    Those from a thousand years past who never deceived the Lord Above—
    Chen Tang and Liu Xiang, two souls of loyalty.
  footnotes:
    - Chen Tang and Liu Xiang were historical figures known for their moral courage in remonstrating with their rulers. Chen Tang served as a trusted advisor and Liu Xiang was known for his wisdom and righteousness in speaking truth to power, even at personal risk.
    - The poem references the author's failure to submit a memorial criticizing court favoritism due to interference by colleagues seeking to protect the emperor's favorites, suggesting the author's regret at compromising his duty.
    - The rank of Remonstrator (正言) was a position specifically designated for officials to advise the ruler and speak against wrongdoing at court.
